# PRODUCT REQUIREMENT DOCUMENT (PRD)

## Project Title: Soccer Telemetry Engine v3.0 (Production Redesign)

**Document Version:** 3.0.0

**Target Architecture:** Object-Oriented Python (OpenCV / NumPy)

**Classification:** Internal Developer Specification

---

## 1. Executive Summary & Context

### 1.1 Objective

The Soccer Telemetry Engine is a high-performance computer vision tool designed to analyze soccer strike kinematics, tracking the flight trajectory of a ball and the dynamic positioning of a striker's foot. The engine translates raw 2D pixel coordinates into a perspective-corrected 3D flight trajectory, calculating launching angles, shot types, and telemetry metrics.

### 1.2 Version 3.0 Regression Root-Cause Analysis

Following the integration of perspective-correction logic, a major functional regression was observed during initial testing:

* **The Symptom:** "Low Driven / Power Shots" were systematically misclassified as "Long Balls", and vice versa.
* **The Root Cause:** OpenCV coordinates map the vertical Y-axis with 0 at the absolute top of the frame, increasing downwards. A rising soccer ball moves toward 0, causing a decreasing raw Y value. When the trajectory vector math was rewritten to invert this behavior ($dy_{\text{screen}} = y_{\text{past}} - y_{\text{current}}$), it was implemented without structural guards. This caused signed value errors, negative angle yields, and mathematical domain errors when tracking frames momentarily degraded.

This PRD establishes the technical blueprint to structurally eliminate these errors using absolute mathematical defenses, decoupled state tracking, and an object-oriented Python pipeline.

